# Fixture IRI-007: host case-folding and RDF IRI identity
#
# RFC 3986 §6.2.2.1 and RFC 3987 §5.3.2.1 recommend (SHOULD) lowercasing
# the host component for normalization.  However, RDF Concepts §3.1 defines
# IRI equality as a simple character-by-character string comparison, with
# NO mandatory normalization.
#
# Therefore `http://EXAMPLE.COM/s` and `http://example.com/s` are TWO
# DISTINCT IRIs in RDF, even though they resolve to the same HTTP resource.
#
# Hypothesis A (over-normalization): An implementation that lowercases the
# host during IRI parsing will unify these two subjects, producing a
# spurious merge in the parsed graph.  The diff will see one subject with
# two facts instead of two subjects each with one fact.
#
# Hypothesis B (under-normalization): An implementation that NEVER
# normalizes will correctly preserve both as distinct — but may fail W3C
# interoperability tests that assume normalization occurred.
#
# W3C reference: public-rdf-comments thread "IRI normalization and
# comparison" (2011) clarifies the intentional omission of normalization
# from the RDF spec.
#
# Spec: RFC 3986 §6.2.2.1, RFC 3987 §5.3.2.1, RDF Concepts §3.1

# Subject A: uppercased host — DISTINCT IRI in RDF
<http://EXAMPLE.COM/subject> <http://example.org/pred/label> "uppercase-host" .

# Subject B: lowercased host — DISTINCT IRI in RDF
<http://example.com/subject> <http://example.org/pred/label> "lowercase-host" .

# These are two different subjects. A normalizing parser merges them.
# The predicate IRI is identical in both — normalized to lowercase already.
